e,"ts_un":false,"ts_fgc":"#000000","ts_un_i":true,"ts_fgc_i":true,"ts_it":true,"ts_fs":13.0,"ts_ff":"Verdana","ts_it_i":false,"ts_bgc":"#c5e1a5","ts_fs_i":false,"ts_bgc_i":false}},{"ty":"as","st":"text","si":7463,"ei":7480,"sm":{"ts_ff_i":false,"ts_un":false,"ts_fgc":"#757575","ts_un_i":true,"ts_fgc_i":false,"ts_fs":11.0,"ts_ff":"Roboto","ts_fs_i":false}},{"ty":"as","st":"text","si":7500,"ei":8262,"sm":{"ts_ff_i":false,"ts_un":false,"ts_fgc":"#000000","ts_un_i":true,"ts_fgc_i":true,"ts_it":true,"ts_fs":13.0,"ts_ff":"Verdana","ts_it_i":false,"ts_bgc":"#ffb8a1","ts_fs_i":false,"ts_bgc_i":false}},{"ty":"as","st":"text","si":8263,"ei":8280,"sm":{"ts_ff_i":false,"ts_un":false,"ts_fgc":"#757575","ts_un_i":true,"ts_fgc_i":false,"ts_fs":11.0,"ts_ff":"Roboto","ts_fs_i":false}}]; DOCS_modelChunkLoadStart = new Date().getTime(); _getTimingInstance().incrementTime('', DOCS_modelChunkLoadStart - DOCS_modelChunkParseStart); DOCS_warmStartDocumentLoader.loadModelChunk(DOCS_modelChunk); DOCS_modelChunk = undefined;</script><script type="text/javascript" nonce="Wl56Lf1fK3stGBU/Ktztpw">DOCS_modelChunkParseStart = new Date().getTime();</script><script type="text/javascript" nonce="Wl56Lf1fK3stGBU/Ktztpw">DOCS_modelChunk = [{"ty":"is","ibi":8290,"s":"\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001c\"The infantry radio channel sounded like an old war movie. Colonel Moore, Trojan 6, came across calm and commanding. [His voice] rang with courage and sound judgment. It made men of boys in X-Ray that day. \u0027, understand your situation ... keep steady ... we are going to drop artillery all around you. Get your men ... all of them ... and walk together slowly back as\n\nJanuary 16, 2019\n\u001c136\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cthe shells impact. Just walk back with the artillery and you will be OK. Hang in there.\u0027 \"\n\nJanuary 16, 2019\n\u001c136\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001c\"Our Huey skimmed the trees and headed north out of harm\u0027s way. I lit up a cigarette, turned to my left an dover my shoulder saw a very bloody trooper laid out with his head in another trooper\u0027s lap. I passed the cigarette back, lit another and stuck it in the bloody\n\nJanuary 16, 2019\n\u001c138\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001ctrooper\u0027s mouth.At that moment the trooper with the bloody back looked me squarely in the eyes and gave me one of the most cherished thank you\u0027s I have ever received.\n\nJanuary 16, 2019\n\u001c139\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cA commander in battle has three means of influencing the action: Fire support, now pouring down in torrents; his personal presence on the battlefield; and the use of his reserve.\n\nJanuary 16, 2019\n\u001c140\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cThe Scriptures say that there is no greater love than to lay down your life for your friends. This is what Calvin Bouknight did in that fire-filled jungle. He sheltered the wounded he was treating with his own body, his back to the enemy guns, completely vulnerable.\n\nJanuary 16, 2019\n\u001c145\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cDeal was helping in the evacuation of casualties when he was brought up short by a strange sight. \"It was at this time that one of the things I regret most about that battle occurred. I saw a line, not a column, just a line of men, probably two hundred strong, moving on my right flank in the same direction as we were about to turn, the east, and move in with our casualties. I immediately lifted my weapon, had them in my sights with a clear shot. I started to call for\n\nJanuary 16, 2019\n\u001c146\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cthose near me to get their weapons up because I thought they were North Vietnamese. But it was just a little bit too far to distinguish if they were Americans or North Vietnamese, so I elected not to fire.\"There was also fear of drawing attention to our depleted platoon. My men were now all killed or wounded except for the equivalent of two squads, about eighteen or so left. These two hundred troops were parallel to us, making their way to the landing zone. Marm, who had been on my right, had already withdrawn. It turned out that they were some of the North Vietnamese we had to fight later that day, who inflicted fearsome casualties on us. I only regret that we didn\u0027t stand there and start shooting them.\"\n\nJanuary 16, 2019\n\u001c146\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cThere are only three principles of warfare: Audacity, Audacity, and audacity!\n\nJanuary 16, 2019\n\u001c147\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001c--General George S. Patton\n\nJanuary 16, 2019\n\u001c147\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cSergeant Sam Hollman, Jr., a native Pennsylvanian, knelt beside his mortally wounded buddy Jack Gell and heard him gasp, \"Tell my wife I love her.\"\n\nJanuary 16, 2019\n\u001c153\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cSuddenly, twenty-five yards away, Deal saw an American get up and charge forward while everyone around him was flat on his belly. Says Deal, \"I saw him throw a grenade behind an anthill and empty his weapon into it. Then he fell to his knees. I said to myself: \u0027, get up, don\u0027t be hurt.\u0027 I didn\u0027t know who it was; I couldn\u0027t make out the form. There was so much battlefield haze, dust, smoke.\"It was Lieutenant Joe Marm. He had spotted an enemy machine gun dug into a big termite hill;\n\nJanuary 16, 2019\n\u001c154\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cit was chewing up both the Bravo Company platoons.After failing to knock it out with a LAW rocket and a thrown grenade, he decided to deal with it directly. He charged through the fire, tossed a hand grenade behind the hill, and then cleaned up the survivors with his M-16 rifle. The following day, Lieutenant Al Devney found a dead North Vietnamese officer and eleven enemy soldiers sprawled behind that termite mound. Says Deal, \"Joe Marm saved my life and the lives of many others.\"Lieutenant Marm suffered a bullet wound to his neck and jaw. Staff Sergeant Les Staley, thirty-eight, of Pike County, Kentucky, ran out and, with a private, got the wounded lieutenant to his feet. Supporting him, they joined a growing stream of walking wounded flowing back toward the battalion aid station. Sergeant Keeton treated Marm\u0027s wound, and one of Bruce Crandalfs Hueys evacuated him to the rear. Within days, Lieutenant Joe Marm was recuperating at Valley Forge Army Hospital near his home in Pennsylvania.\n\nJanuary 16, 2019\n\u001c154\n\u0011\n\u0011"},{"ty":"te","id":"i.18","spi":8297},{"ty":"te","id":"i.19","spi":8703},{"ty":"te","id":"i.20","spi":8832},{"ty":"te","id":"i.21","spi":9138},{"ty":"te","id":"i.22","spi":9343},{"ty":"te","id":"i.23","spi":9560},{"ty":"te","id":"i.24","spi":9865},{"ty":"te","id":"i.25","spi":10375},{"ty":"te","id":"i.26","spi":11128},{"ty":"te","id":"i.27","spi":11244},{"ty":"te","id":"i.28","spi":11309},{"ty":"te","id":"i.29","spi":11495},{"ty":"te","id":"i.30","spi":12019},{"ty":"as","st":"tbl","si":8290,"ei":8290,"sm":{"tbls_cols":{"cv":{"op":"set","opValue":[{"col_wv":468.0,"col_wt":0}]}},"tbls_bw":0.75,"tbls_bc":"#bdbdbd"}},{"ty":"as","st":"cell","si":8292,"ei":8292,"sm":{"cell_pb_i":false,"cell_pr_i":false,"cell_pt_i":false,"cell_pt":0.0,"cell_pb":0.0,"cell_pr":0.0,"cell_pl_i":false,"cell_pl":0.0}},{"ty":"as","st":"tbl","si":8294,"ei":8294,"sm":{"tbls_cols":{"cv":{"op":"set","opValue":[{"col_wv":54.0,"col_wt":0},{"col_wv":358.5,"col_wt":0},{"col_wv":54.0,"col_wt":0}]}},"tbls_bw":0.0}},{"ty":"as","st":"cell","si":8296,"ei":8296,"sm":{"cell_pr_i":false,"cell_bl":{},"cell_pt_i":false,"cell_bb_i":false,"cell_pt":0.0,"cell_bt":{},"cell_pb":0.0,